'''Kannoni-in''' (観音院), also known as '''Kosaka Kannoni-in''', is a Buddhist temple of the {{ill|Shingon Buddhism Chisan-ha|ja|真言宗智山派|1=Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|12=draft|12=draft}} sect located in {{ill|Okaya|ja|岡谷市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Nagano Prefecture, Japan. The temple's mountain name (''sangō'') is '''Ryūkōzan''' (龍光山), and its principal object of worship is the {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|lt=Eleven-Faced Avalokitesvara|ja|十一面観音|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== History ==
Originally a {{ill|Shabō|ja|社坊|12=draft|12=draft}} (a temple associated with a Shinto shrine) of {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kannoni-in served as a {{ill|Prayer Temple|ja|祈願所|1=Kigan-sho|12=draft|12=draft}} for the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏|1=Suwa clan|12=draft|12=draft}} during the medieval period. The temple is situated on a hill overlooking {{ill|Lake Suwa|ja|諏訪湖|12=draft|12=draft}}, providing a scenic view of the surrounding area.

The temple was revived during the early Edo period under the patronage of {{ill|Suwa Tadatane|ja|諏訪忠恒|12=draft|12=draft}}, the lord of the {{ill|Suwa Domain|ja|諏訪藩|12=draft|12=draft}}. The current main hall was rebuilt in 1715 (Shōtoku 5) by {{ill|Suwa Tadatora|ja|諏訪忠虎|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The temple is featured in {{ill|Yasushi Inoue|ja|井上靖|12=draft|12=draft}}'s historical novel *{{ill|Fūrin Kazan (novel)|ja|風林火山 (小説)|12=draft|12=draft}}*, where it serves as the residence of {{ill|Yufu-hime|ja|諏訪御料人|12=draft|12=draft}}, a concubine of {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|12=draft|12=draft}} and the mother of {{ill|Takeda Katsuyori|ja|武田勝頼|12=draft|12=draft}}. The 2007 NHK {{ill|Taiga Drama|ja|大河ドラマ|12=draft|12=draft}} adaptation of *Fūrin Kazan* also portrays the temple.

In 1963 (Shōwa 38), a memorial tower dedicated to Suwa Goryōnin was erected on the temple grounds.

