'''Kannoni-in''' (観音院), also known as '''Kosaka Kannoni-in''', is a Buddhist temple of the {{ill|Shingon Buddhism Chisan-ha|ja|真言宗智山派|1=Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shingon Buddhism Chisan-ha|13=User:Immanuelle/Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|qq=}} sect located in {{ill|Okaya|ja|岡谷市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okaya|qq=}}, Nagano Prefecture, Japan. The temple's mountain name (''sangō'') is '''Ryūkōzan''' (龍光山), and its principal object of worship is the {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|lt=Eleven-Faced Avalokitesvara|ja|十一面観音|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ekādaśamukha|qq=}}.

== History ==
Originally a {{ill|Shabō|ja|社坊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shabō|qq=}} (a temple associated with a Shinto shrine) of {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Taisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa-taisha|qq=}}, Kannoni-in served as a {{ill|Prayer Temple|ja|祈願所|1=Kigan-sho|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prayer Temple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kigan-sho|qq=}} for the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏|1=Suwa clan|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa clan|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa clan|qq=}} during the medieval period. The temple is situated on a hill overlooking {{ill|Lake Suwa|ja|諏訪湖|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Lake Suwa|qq=}}, providing a scenic view of the surrounding area.

The temple was revived during the early Edo period under the patronage of {{ill|Suwa Tadatane|ja|諏訪忠恒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Tadatane|qq=}}, the lord of the {{ill|Suwa Domain|ja|諏訪藩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Domain|qq=}}. The current main hall was rebuilt in 1715 (Shōtoku 5) by {{ill|Suwa Tadatora|ja|諏訪忠虎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Tadatora|qq=}}.

The temple is featured in {{ill|Yasushi Inoue|ja|井上靖|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasushi Inoue|qq=}}'s historical novel *{{ill|Fūrin Kazan (novel)|ja|風林火山 (小説)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fūrin Kazan (novel)|qq=}}*, where it serves as the residence of {{ill|Yufu-hime|ja|諏訪御料人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yufu-hime|qq=}}, a concubine of {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda Shingen|qq=}} and the mother of {{ill|Takeda Katsuyori|ja|武田勝頼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda Katsuyori|qq=}}. The 2007 NHK {{ill|Taiga Drama|ja|大河ドラマ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taiga Drama|qq=}} adaptation of *Fūrin Kazan* also portrays the temple.

In 1963 (Shōwa 38), a memorial tower dedicated to Suwa Goryōnin was erected on the temple grounds.

== Cultural Properties ==
* '''Main Hall''' - Rebuilt in 1715 (Shōtoku 5) by Suwa Tadatora.
* '''Memorial Tower''' - Dedicated to Suwa Goryōnin in 1963.

== References ==
* ''Shinshu Culture Series: Temples and Shrines'' (1981). Shinano Mainichi Shimbun.
* ''Exploring Shinshu's Ancient Temples: Tendai and Shingon Sects'' (1996). Kyodo Publishing.

