{{Infobox religious building | name = Kannoni-in | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] |image = {{image requested|cat=岡谷市}} | location = Minato 4-chome 15-22, Okaya, Nagano Prefecture, Japan | latitude_deg = 36 | latitude_min = 2 | latitude_sec = 6.7 | longitude_deg = 138 | longitude_min = 4 | longitude_sec = 7.1 | sect = [[:en:Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|Shingon-shū Chisan-ha]] | deity = [[:en:Ekādaśamukha|Eleven-Faced Avalokitesvara]] | founded = | founder = | full_name = Ryūkōzan Kannoni-in | former_affiliation = [[:en:Suwa-taisha|Suwa-taisha]] (Shabō) | noteworthy = Historical ties to {{ill|Suwa Goryōnin|ja|諏訪御料人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Goryōnin|qq=}} | map = Nagano Prefecture | map_relief = yes | map_width = 256 }} '''Kannoni-in''' (観音院), also known as '''Kosaka Kannoni-in''', is a Buddhist temple of the [[:en:Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|Shingon-shū Chisan-ha]] sect located in [[:en:Okaya, Nagano|Okaya]], Nagano Prefecture, Japan. The temple's mountain name (''sangō'') is '''Ryūkōzan''' (龍光山), and its principal object of worship is the [[:en:Ekādaśamukha|Eleven-Faced Avalokitesvara]].
== History == Originally a {{ill|Shabō|ja|社坊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shabō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 神宮寺}} (a temple associated with a Shinto shrine) of [[:en:Suwa-taisha|Suwa-taisha]], Kannoni-in served as a {{ill|Prayer Temple|ja|祈願所|1=Kigan-sho|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prayer Temple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kigan-sho|qq=}} for the [[:en:Suwa clan|Suwa clan]] during the medieval period. The temple is situated on a hill overlooking [[:en:Lake Suwa|Lake Suwa]], providing a scenic view of the surrounding area.
The temple was revived during the early Edo period under the patronage of {{ill|Suwa Tadatane|ja|諏訪忠恒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Tadatane|qq=}}, the lord of the [[:en:Suwa Domain|Suwa Domain]]. The current main hall was rebuilt in 1715 (Shōtoku 5) by {{ill|Suwa Tadatora|ja|諏訪忠虎|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Tadatora|qq=}}.
The temple is featured in [[:en:Yasushi Inoue|Yasushi Inoue]]'s historical novel *{{ill|Fūrin Kazan (novel)|ja|風林火山 (小説)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fūrin Kazan (novel)|qq=}}*, where it serves as the residence of {{ill|Yufu-hime|ja|諏訪御料人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yufu-hime|qq=}}, a concubine of {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda Shingen|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and the mother of [[:en:Takeda Katsuyori|Takeda Katsuyori]]. The 2007 NHK [[:en:Taiga drama|Taiga Drama]] adaptation of *Fūrin Kazan* also portrays the temple.
In 1963 (Shōwa 38), a memorial tower dedicated to Suwa Goryōnin was erected on the temple grounds.
== Cultural Properties == * '''Main Hall''' - Rebuilt in 1715 (Shōtoku 5) by Suwa Tadatora. * '''Memorial Tower''' - Dedicated to Suwa Goryōnin in 1963.
== References == * ''Shinshu Culture Series: Temples and Shrines'' (1981). Shinano Mainichi Shimbun. * ''Exploring Shinshu's Ancient Temples: Tendai and Shingon Sects'' (1996). Kyodo Publishing.
== See Also == * {{ill|Kosaka Castle|ja|小坂城 (岡谷市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kosaka Castle|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} * {{ill|Minato Village|ja|湊村 (長野県)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minato Village|qq=}} * {{ill|Okaya City Landmarks|ja|岡谷市#名所・旧跡・観光スポット|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okaya City Landmarks|qq=}}
