'''Kannoni-in''' (観音院), also known as '''Kosaka Kannoni-in''', is a Buddhist temple of the {{ill|Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|en|Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|qid=Q674374|lt=Shingon-shū Chisan-ha|1=Shingon-shū Chisan-ha}} sect located in {{ill|Okaya, Nagano|en|Okaya, Nagano|qid=Q838672|lt=Okaya|1=Okaya, Nagano}}, Nagano Prefecture, Japan. The temple's mountain name (''sangō'') is '''Ryūkōzan''' (龍光山), and its principal object of worship is the {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|en|Ekādaśamukha|qid=Q11404731|lt=Eleven-Faced Avalokitesvara|1=Ekādaśamukha}}.

== History ==
Originally a {{ill|Shabō|ja|社坊|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shabō|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 神宮寺|1=Jingū-ji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q1074971}} (a temple associated with a Shinto shrine) of {{ill|Suwa-taisha|en|Suwa-taisha|qid=Q218813|lt=Suwa-taisha|1=Suwa-taisha}}, Kannoni-in served as a {{ill|Prayer Temple|ja|祈願所|1=Kigan-sho|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Prayer Temple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kigan-sho|qq=}} for the {{ill|Suwa clan|en|Suwa clan|qid=Q2975376|lt=Suwa clan|1=Suwa clan}} during the medieval period. The temple is situated on a hill overlooking {{ill|Lake Suwa|en|Lake Suwa|qid=Q1206692|lt=Lake Suwa|1=Lake Suwa}}, providing a scenic view of the surrounding area.

The temple was revived during the early Edo period under the patronage of {{ill|Suwa Tadatane|ja|諏訪忠恒|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Tadatane|1=Suwa Tadatsune|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11631876}}, the lord of the {{ill|Suwa Domain|en|Suwa Domain|qid=Q3034531|lt=Suwa Domain|1=Suwa Domain}}. The current main hall was rebuilt in 1715 (Shōtoku 5) by {{ill|Suwa Tadatora|ja|諏訪忠虎|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Tadatora|1=Suwa Tadatora|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11631882}}.

The temple is featured in {{ill|Yasushi Inoue|en|Yasushi Inoue|qid=Q712734|lt=Yasushi Inoue|1=Yasushi Inoue}}'s historical novel *{{ill|Fūrin Kazan (novel)|ja|風林火山 (小説)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fūrin Kazan (novel)|1=The Samurai Banner of Furin Kazan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11665512}}*, where it serves as the residence of {{ill|Yufu-hime|ja|諏訪御料人|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yufu-hime|1=Suwa Goronin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q8193299}}, a concubine of [[Takeda Shingen]]{{efn|Japanese feudal lord (1521–1573)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda Shingen|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and the mother of {{ill|Takeda Katsuyori|en|Takeda Katsuyori|qid=Q662482|lt=Takeda Katsuyori|1=Takeda Katsuyori}}. The 2007 NHK {{ill|Taiga drama|en|Taiga drama|qid=Q1200935|lt=Taiga Drama|1=Taiga drama}} adaptation of *Fūrin Kazan* also portrays the temple.

In 1963 (Shōwa 38), a memorial tower dedicated to Suwa Goryōnin was erected on the temple grounds.

== Cultural Properties ==
* '''Main Hall''' - Rebuilt in 1715 (Shōtoku 5) by Suwa Tadatora.
* '''Memorial Tower''' - Dedicated to Suwa Goryōnin in 1963.

